# Maximum Building Height (LeetCode 1840)

## 📌 Problem Statement

You are given:

* An integer `n` representing `n` buildings numbered from `1` to `n`.
* A list of restrictions where:

```text
restrictions[i] = [id, maxHeight]
```

meaning building `id` cannot exceed `maxHeight`.

Additionally:

* Building `1` must have height `0`.
* The height difference between adjacent buildings cannot exceed `1`.

Return the maximum possible height of any building after satisfying all restrictions.

---

## 🧠 Approach

### Key Observation

Because adjacent buildings can differ by at most `1`, every restriction affects nearby buildings.

For two restricted buildings:

```text
(id1, h1)
(id2, h2)
```

their heights must satisfy:

```text
|h1 - h2| ≤ id2 - id1
```

Some restrictions may therefore become tighter after considering neighboring restrictions.

---

### Step 1: Add Building 1

Building `1` always has height `0`.

```cpp
arr.push_back({1, 0});
```

Then insert all given restrictions and sort by building index.

---

### Step 2: Left-to-Right Propagation

For every restriction:

```text
height[i] ≤ height[i-1] + distance
```

because the height can increase by at most `1` per building.

```cpp
arr[i][1] = min(arr[i][1],
                arr[i-1][1] + distance);
```

This removes impossible heights.

---

### Step 3: Right-to-Left Propagation

Similarly:

```text
height[i] ≤ height[i+1] + distance
```

```cpp
arr[i][1] = min(arr[i][1],
                arr[i+1][1] + distance);
```

After these two passes, all restrictions become mutually consistent.

---

### Step 4: Find the Maximum Peak

Between two restricted buildings:

```text
(x1, h1)
(x2, h2)
```

the highest achievable peak occurs by increasing from one side and decreasing toward the other.

The maximum height in that interval is:

Compute this value for every consecutive pair of restrictions.

---

### Step 5: Handle Buildings After the Last Restriction

If the last restriction is at position `p` with height `h`:

the height can continue increasing by `1` per building until building `n`.

The maximum possible height becomes:

Take the maximum among all candidates.

---

## 💻 Code (C++)

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int maxBuilding(int n, vector<vector<int>>& restrictions) {
        vector<vector<int>> arr;

        arr.push_back({1, 0});

        for (auto &r : restrictions) {
            arr.push_back(r);
        }

        sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());

        // Left to right pass
        for (int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
            int d = arr[i][0] - arr[i - 1][0];
            arr[i][1] = min(arr[i][1], arr[i - 1][1] + d);
        }

        // Right to left pass
        for (int i = arr.size() - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            int d = arr[i + 1][0] - arr[i][0];
            arr[i][1] = min(arr[i][1], arr[i + 1][1] + d);
        }

        int ans = 0;

        for (int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
            int x1 = arr[i - 1][0];
            int h1 = arr[i - 1][1];

            int x2 = arr[i][0];
            int h2 = arr[i][1];

            int d = x2 - x1;

            ans = max(ans, (h1 + h2 + d) / 2);
        }

        int lastPos = arr.back()[0];
        int lastH = arr.back()[1];

        ans = max(ans, lastH + (n - lastPos));

        return ans;
    }
};
```

---

## 🚀 Example

### Input

```text
n = 5
restrictions = [[2,1],[4,1]]
```

### Valid Heights

```text
Building: 1  2  3  4  5
Height:   0  1  2  1  2
```

### Output

```text
2
```

